    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "657c828ca858b33e",
      "text": "Alone, in all institutional spheres of operation, unavailabilities are surprisingly not only unavoidable, but downright indispensable, if we look closely: Every teacher knows that formative educational processes take place outside the curriculum, not infrequently at the very stages when the curriculum, which attempts to stipulate when what must be learned and mastered, no longer plays a role; every head of a research and development department is aware that real innovations, groundbreaking (\"disruptive\") discoveries can neither be forced nor predicted; every doctor is aware that (at least in the case of serious illnesses) healing is also based on uncontrollable self-efficacy. The entertainment industry thrives on the fact that market successes can also be made unavailable, not by money and not by technology: a book, a movie, a song can have been reviewed and rejected by all the major publishers and still become a global hit, and conversely it can flop even though millions have been invested in advertising. Sports and especially commercial soccer would become completely uninteresting if success could simply be bought and technically calculated.\n"
    },
