      "type": "edit",
      "id": "d12360b109e72874",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "d12360b109e72874",
        "text": "The structural dimension of the basic conflict of modernity is shown by the fact that a society that is only able to stabilise itself dynamically cannot accept unavailability, although it needs it everywhere. The compulsion for constant increase inherent in the logics of growth, acceleration and innovation compression implies that efficiency and output or process and result must be constantly optimised at all levels. The element of unavailability that is characteristic of resonance relationships, on the other hand, requires engaging in processes whose occurrence is uncertain and which, moreover, are also open-ended. In other words, one does not know whether resonance will occur, much less what the outcome will be. No company or authority can afford this: optimisation means achieving the best possible result in the shortest possible time while maintaining control over the process. Calculating and mastering are the basic modes of process control in business, politics, care, education, etc. Strictly speaking, the criterion of time and cost pressure alone is enough to illustrate the problem: Someone who has to get to the airport under time pressure must not get involved in any conversation, idea, landscape, music or people crossing his or her path, otherwise he or she will miss the plane. If you want to pass an exam, you must not let anyone or anything \"reach\" you, you must not take any detours, you must not get involved in anything that cannot be predicted in terms of time and content. Those who have to charge for care services on a minute-by-minute basis cannot afford any interaction with the cared for that is open-ended, and no university may offer training courses where it is not clear how long they will last and what competences will be acquired. No health insurance company can get involved in a treatment method whose duration and success is doubtful - psychoanalytically working therapists know a thing or two about this - and no one wants to pay for a research programme that is open-ended. The output must be right, and it must be predictable and controllable in terms of time and content; that is what the institutional logic of dynamic stabilisation demands.\n Translated with www.DeepL.com/Translator (free version)"
